---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-poland', text: 'Leaving Polish Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'eu-movement', text: 'Moving Within the EU', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-poland', text: 'Returning to Poland', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Allianz Care Review', href: '/providers/allianz-care' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best UK Expat Insurance', href: '/best/uk-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best German Expat Insurance', href: '/best/german-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'polishSupport', header: 'Polish Support' },
  { key: 'euNetwork', header: 'EU Network' },
  { key: 'polandCoverage', header: 'Poland Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', polishSupport: 'Limited', euNetwork: 'Strong', polandCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€170/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', polishSupport: 'Yes', euNetwork: 'Excellent', polandCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', polishSupport: 'Limited', euNetwork: 'Strong', polandCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Signal Iduna', polishSupport: 'Yes', euNetwork: 'Strong', polandCoverage: 'Included', price: '€150/mo' },
  { provider: 'Inter Partner', polishSupport: 'Yes', euNetwork: 'Good', polandCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€140/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Polish Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Polish expats. Find coverage for the UK, Germany, Netherlands, and other popular destinations."
  headline="Best Insurance for Polish Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Poles are among Europe's most mobile populations. Here's how to stay covered whether you're in London, Berlin, Amsterdam, or beyond."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/polish-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Polish expats are concentrated in the UK, Germany, Netherlands, Ireland, and Norway. Your insurance needs depend on whether you're staying in the EU/EEA (where coordination rules apply) or going further. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Polish expats going worldwide. Strong networks everywhere, reliable service, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Excellent for EU destinations. Strong European networks, good Polish support, competitive pricing.</li>
    <li><strong>Signal Iduna:</strong> German insurer popular with Polish expats. Good EU coverage, Polish service available, includes Poland coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent UK networks. Ideal for Poles in Britain.</li>
    <li><strong>Inter Partner Assistance:</strong> Budget-friendly EU coverage. Good basic option for cost-conscious expats.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="EU vs Non-EU"
    description="If you're moving within the EU, social security coordination may affect your insurance needs. Working in another EU country often enrolls you in that country's system. Outside the EU, you definitely need international insurance."
    buttonText="Compare Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-poland">Leaving Polish Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Poland's NFZ (Narodowy Fundusz Zdrowia) provides public healthcare to insured residents. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>NFZ Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    NFZ coverage is linked to social insurance contributions (ZUS). When you stop contributing in Poland—typically when you leave employment or deregister residence—your NFZ coverage eventually ends. The EKUZ (European Health Insurance Card) provides emergency coverage in the EU but not routine care.
  </p>

  <h3>ZUS Contributions</h3>
  <p>
    Your ZUS contributions affect pension rights as well as healthcare. If you're working in another EU country, those contributions count toward your Polish pension through EU coordination. Outside the EU, Poland has limited bilateral agreements.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Polish Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Polish private insurance (PZU, Medicover, LUX MED) is designed for Polish residents. International coverage is typically limited to short-term emergencies. For long-term stays abroad, you need dedicated international coverage.
  </p>

  <h2 id="eu-movement">Moving Within the EU</h2>
  <p>
    Moving to another EU country triggers social security coordination rules:
  </p>

  <h3>If You're Employed</h3>
  <p>
    Working in another EU country generally enrolls you in that country's social security system. Your employer makes contributions locally, and you're covered by local healthcare. You may not need separate international insurance—but you might want it for:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Faster access than public healthcare provides</li>
    <li>Coverage during visits to Poland</li>
    <li>Access to Polish-speaking doctors</li>
    <li>Continuity if you change countries again</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>If You're Self-Employed</h3>
  <p>
    Self-employment in another EU country is more complex. You may be able to remain in the Polish system while working abroad, or you may need to join the destination country's system. Consult ZUS for your specific situation.
  </p>

  <h3>Posted Workers (Delegowanie)</h3>
  <p>
    If your Polish employer sends you to work temporarily in another EU country, you may remain in the Polish system with an A1 certificate. Check with ZUS about posting rules and duration limits.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Brexit Impact</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      The UK left the EU, so EU coordination rules no longer apply automatically. Polish expats in the UK now need to ensure they're enrolled in NHS through proper visa/residence processes. Pre-settled and settled status holders have NHS access.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global is our top recommendation for Polish expats going beyond Europe or wanting comprehensive private coverage. Strong networks worldwide, reliable service, and three coverage tiers with limits up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    Polish-language support is limited, but English service is excellent 24/7. Poland coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Polish expats outside the EU or those wanting premium private coverage in Europe.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers excellent European coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks throughout the EU make this ideal for Poles staying within Europe. Polish support is available, and claims processing is efficient.
  </p>

  <p>
    Plans include mental health, maternity, and chronic condition management. Good value for comprehensive EU coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Polish expats in EU countries who want comprehensive private coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Signal Iduna</h3>
  <p>
    Signal Iduna is a German insurer popular among Polish expats, particularly those in Germany. They understand EU coordination, offer Polish-language support, and include Poland coverage automatically.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pricing is competitive, and service is good. Strong option for Germany-bound Poles.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Polish expats in Germany who want familiar service with Polish support.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium coverage with excellent UK networks. Since the UK is a top Polish expat destination, their strong British network is valuable. Service quality is high throughout.
  </p>

  <p>
    Polish support is limited, but English service is excellent. Premium pricing reflects top-tier coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Polish expats in the UK who want premium private healthcare access.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare EU and International Options"
    description="Within the EU, you may have public healthcare access. International insurance adds private coverage and continuity. Compare your options."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-poland">Returning to Poland</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to Polish healthcare requires re-establishing NFZ coverage:
  </p>

  <h3>If You're Employed</h3>
  <p>
    Employment in Poland automatically enrolls you in ZUS and NFZ. Coverage begins with your first contribution. Family members can be registered as dependents.
  </p>

  <h3>If You're Not Employed</h3>
  <p>
    Register at your local NFZ office. You may need to make voluntary contributions until you find employment or qualify through other means (unemployment benefits, family member's coverage, etc.).
  </p>

  <h3>EU Coordination on Return</h3>
  <p>
    If you worked in another EU country, bring your S1/E104 forms showing contribution periods. These help ensure continuous coverage recognition.
  </p>

  <h3>Transition Period</h3>
  <p>
    Keep your international insurance active until NFZ coverage is confirmed. Registration is usually quick, but having overlap prevents gaps.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I use EKUZ in the UK?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Post-Brexit, EKUZ has limited validity in the UK. Polish citizens now need proper residence status for NHS access. International insurance is recommended.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Do I need insurance if I work in Germany?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Germany has mandatory health insurance for workers. Your employer enrolls you in a Krankenkasse. Additional private insurance is optional but can improve access.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about my ZUS pension?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Working in the EU counts toward your Polish pension through coordination. Outside the EU, check if Poland has a bilateral agreement with your destination.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Polish doctors abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">In the UK, Germany, and Netherlands, you can find Polish-speaking doctors in areas with large Polish communities. Your insurer can help locate providers.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Should I keep NFZ coverage?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">If you're working in another EU country, you'll typically be covered there. Maintaining dual coverage is usually unnecessary and may create complications.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about self-employed contractors?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Self-employment across borders is complex. You might remain in Polish ZUS or need to register abroad. Consult both ZUS and the destination country's authority.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Polish expats in the EU often have access to local public healthcare, but international insurance provides better access and continuity. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for worldwide coverage. <strong>Allianz Care</strong> offers excellent value for EU destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Signal Iduna</strong> is ideal for Germany-bound expats with Polish support. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> provides premium coverage for those in the UK.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before you leave, clarify your ZUS situation and understand whether you'll be covered by the destination country's system. International insurance supplements local coverage and ensures you're never without protection.
  </p>

</PageShell>
